Why do I wear a mask in New York?

By Jody Liu

PUBLISHED: March 16,2020

Since the first confirmed cases appeared in Washington state on January 20, the number of new cases in the United States has increased at a slow pace. By February 29, there were only 24 cases, with the exception of a few imported infections, most of which had been evacuated from the diamond princess cruise ship and from Wuhan. But since March 1, the number has risen sharply as a result of an outbreak at a care center for the elderly in Washington State and community-based infections in northern California that have no known source of infection. With the expansion of virus detection, the number is expected to soar in the short term.

Although the United States has advanced medical facilities, according to the experience of Wuhan, when a large number of patients influx, most medical institutions are likely to collapse. At a moment when things seemed to be getting tense, I began to take stock of the masks I had saved.

The surgeon general, Jerome Addams, told the public to stop buying face masks to prevent COVID-19, which could actually increase the risk of infection if worn improperly. To me, that's like saying, if you don't wear your seat belt properly in a car, and it can cause harm, shouldn't you wear your seat belt? If you get into a speedboat with a life jacket that you're not wearing correctly, you're going to get into an accident, so don't wear a life jacket?

America's fight against the plague has always been slow

America's response to the epidemic always seems to be half a step behind. Why are you so late? I think there are several factors. After the siege of Wuhan, Donald Trump's impeachment went to trial in the U.S. Senate at a time when Chinese media coverage of the epidemic was overwhelming, the daily headlines in the U.S. mainstream media were dominated by impeachment, and the coverage of the epidemic was not detailed.

On Jan. 31, DONALD TRUMP announced that Chinese would be barred from entering the country at 5 p.m. EDT on Feb. 2, and ordered a 14 day quarantine for U.S. citizens and permanent residents from China. But the psychological illusion caused by "closing off" is that the virus is a "distant phenomenon" , giving medical staff and the public a false "sense of security" .

Once the outbreak spreads to other countries, it becomes overwhelming. Even before the outbreak hit the United States, Chinese communities and individuals had emptied the market for masks to support their home countries.

In fact, I think, in the United States "closed" before the possible situation is that there has been a virus lurking in the community. In New York state, for example, multiple suspected cases were reported negative before the first diagnosis on March 1. However, the CDC in the United States has had an incident of faulty test kits, and each case has only been tested once, failing to consider the possibility of multiple tests to "turn negative to positive, " coupled with the insufficient number of test kits, there may be untested cases.

By the afternoon of March 8, at least 113 cases had been detected in the New York metropolitan area, which includes New York and surrounding states of New Jersey and Connecticut. The largest portion of the infections came from a superbug in Westchester County, New York, and nearly all of the 82 confirmed cases came from the lawyer, who works at the Midtown Manhattan. This is the second confirmed case in New York State and the first case of community transmission.

U.S. health experts say the Donald Trump administration's mixed signals have left Americans unprepared for a public health crisis and delayed their understanding of the virus. As of midnight on March 9 in Mitō, the virus had spread to at least 32 states.

America's health care and basic public health services are of a high standard, but the credibility of the Donald Trump administration has been put to the test by how to avoid public panic and provide critical information and a decisive response, trying to find an effective balance will be a matter of focus for the media and the public.

Not long ago, whistleblowers petitioned the U.S. CDC to report that Department of Health and Human Services personnel not only failed to wear appropriate clothing when they came into contact with Americans evacuating from China at two military bases in California, the personal protective equipment said, and he's moving around outside the base.

At a recent conference on the new coronavirus at Harvard, Balibo Loum, Cameroon, chair professor of Public Health Research at Harvard, said there are 17 agencies in the U.S. federal government that deal with the epidemic, each has its own authority, funding and management. The White House once had an office of pandemic preparedness, with regular phone calls to representatives of all 17 government agencies. So in theory, the federal government could in fact do anything to prevent an outbreak of infectious disease in the United States, but with the health care system in tatters, states have their own health care and funding problems.

"Are the 17 agencies in daily contact with public health authorities in the 50 states? Do the 50 states maintain contact with public health officials in every city and town? After the H1N1 outbreak, the United States developed an important national influenza plan, including how to organize and plan such communication, how to respond in advance, etc. . The situation in the United States, however, is that until yesterday, this office in the White House no longer exists, and there was no one on the National Security Council dedicated to the issue ...... When a New York Times reporter asked: Is the United States ready for a truly serious epidemic? For now, I regret to say: The US was ready, but only once,"said Loum, Cameroon of Balibo.

Medical expenses and paid sick leave

One of the challenges in preventing outbreaks is the structure of the U. S. health insurance system. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, about 7 percent of U.S. adults lacked health insurance in 2018, making it expensive to see a doctor, emergency care or emergency room.

According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 28 percent of uninsured 18, to 65 year olds have been unable to pay for their care in the past year. Another report shows that more than a quarter of American adults delay essential health care because of the state of the economy. Many of those without health insurance are illegal immigrants. Lack of identity is another important reason for these people to refuse to see a doctor.

Even for legal citizens, the lack of insurance is a hurdle. Take Frankie Ushchinskiy, who lived in Wuhan, China, for 15 years. His Chinese wife, who is not a U.S. citizen and has pneumonia, returned to the United States with their daughter on a government evacuation flight, but without health insurance, he received $3,918 in bills from him and his daughter for quarantine and coronavirus testing. After being reported by the New York Times, the hospital spokesman who provided the test said the bill was incorrect and therefore he did not have to pay.

The Donald Trump administration announced in early March that testing for the virus would be a basic health benefit. Under the affordable Care Act, health insurance for large employers must cover costs such as preventive testing. But for individuals, these tests are not necessarily free.

A number of states, including New York and Washington, have issued emergency orders instructing state-regulated health insurers to waive any out-of-pocket fees for patients requiring new coronavirus testing. Some health insurance companies have also announced exemption from out-of-pocket costs for testing related to the new coronavirus. But depending on the type of health insurance, the coverage, and the insurer, the cost to patients may vary.

The United States is one of the developed countries with no statutory paid sick leave. According to the United States Department of Labor, more than a quarter of private sector workers do not receive such benefits, including more than half of those in the lowest 25 percent of wages who are not paid when they are on sick leave.

To make matters worse, many people who do not have access to paid sick leave work in childcare, restaurants, hotels and travel, where the nature of their work requires daily contact with many people who are not only themselves high risk groups, could also help spread the virus. More than two fifths of workers in these services do not have paid sick leave, according to the United States Department of Labor.

With private companies such as the Walmart and SAM clubs introducing a new emergency paid leave policy, Vice President Michel Pensée said the White House was working with Congressional leaders to address that concern.

Mask Myth

New York City has the largest and most concentrated Chinese population of any city outside Asia and in the United States, accounting for an estimated 6 percent of the city's population in 2014, and many of them maintain close business ties with China. New York, the world's capital, has struggled to trace the source of the virus as a second wave has spread through Asia, the Middle East and Europe. On March 7, List of Governors of New York Andrew declared a state of emergency. Remaining calm, he said, was not a priority but an expansion of the test.

I couldn't agree more. Metropolitan areas like New York City have a resident population of 8.623 million, of which Manhattan I. Has a population of about 1.63 million. Squeezed into about 60 square kilometers of land, the average population density is 27,346 people per square kilometer. On this small island, there are numerous "high flying people" from all over the world and ethnic groups from all over the world. The virus from all over the world can be transported to the mainland within 24 hours, plus a variety of miscellaneous hygiene habits, some illegal immigrants are afraid to go to the doctor.

Do you think I should wear a mask in the event of an outbreak?

Health care workers will need 3.5 billion face masks if an outbreak of the new coronavirus reaches pandemic proportions in the United States, the Department of Health and Human Services said March 4. However, according to CNBC, the US emergency stockpile currently includes about 12m N95 masks and 30m surgical masks, about 1 per cent of the required number.

The U.S. House of Representatives and Senate reached a resolution on March 4 to set aside $8.3 billion in emergency funds to deal with the growing outbreak in the United States, the approved funds will be used to purchase approximately 500 million N95 masks over the next 18 months.

I don't think it's primarily a question of how much trust society has in each other, it's a question of cultural differences. I believe that if the outbreak breaks out in New York, New Yorkers outside the Chinese community will start wearing masks. One reason Americans don't wear masks is that much of the United States looks like a suburban area -- a residential area consisting of detached villas connected by roads to retail centers and office buildings. According to the 2017 U.S. housing survey, released by the U.S. government in 2018, about 52 percent of the country's nearly 76,000 households said they lived in the suburbs, while about 27 percent said they lived in cities and 21 percent said they lived in the countryside. As a result, most Americans feel that they live in a less densely populated suburb and don't need to wear a mask.

An even more important factor is that the perception of face masks in mainland China, Hong Kong, Taiwan and other Asian countries and regions has changed radically since the SARS epidemic, and masks no longer carry negative social labels. The European and American countries were not personally affected by a large area of the threat of SARS virus infection, there is no "mask culture. ".

But over the years, no matter what season, I always go out to put a mask or two in the bag and a few packets of alcohol disinfection tablets, is caught off guard in public to bump into a big cough, but not cover up the mouth of the wicked ghost.

I believe that since the outbreak is directly linked to supply chain trends, and in Donald Trump's view, the stock market will have a direct impact on his re election campaign, he should be working hard to prevent a worsening of the epidemic before long. But until Donald Trump's response becomes more credible, I'm going to put on my mask.
